Overview

Gesture-Based Assistive Communication Using TinyML & FSK is an embedded assistive technology system that enables individuals with speech or motor impairments to communicate through hand gestures. The system detects gestures using motion sensors, processes the data using lightweight machine learning models deployed with TinyML, and transmits the interpreted information using Frequency Shift Keying (FSK) communication.

The goal of this project is to develop a portable, affordable, and real-time assistive communication solution that operates on embedded hardware without relying on cloud-based processing. By combining sensor data analysis, embedded AI, and digital communication techniques, the system provides an efficient and scalable approach to improving communication accessibility.

Problem Statement

Individuals affected by conditions such as paralysis, ALS, stroke, or severe speech impairments often face difficulties expressing their needs. Existing assistive communication systems are often expensive, complex, or require internet connectivity.

This project aims to create a low-cost embedded solution that allows users to communicate through simple gestures, making assistive communication more accessible and practical.

Project Objectives

Develop a gesture recognition system using motion sensors.

Implement TinyML models for real-time classification on embedded hardware.

Use FSK modulation for reliable communication between devices.

Analyze sensor signals and waveform patterns using MATLAB.

Provide real-time visualization and monitoring using a Python interface.

System Architecture
1. Motion Sensing Module

An MPU6050 accelerometer and gyroscope captures motion and orientation data generated by hand gestures.

2. Embedded Processing

A microcontroller processes the sensor data and runs a TinyML model that classifies the detected gestures.

3. Signal Processing & Analysis

MATLAB is used to:

Analyze sensor data

Visualize waveform patterns

Study signal behavior

Develop and test signal processing techniques

4. Communication Module

Gesture data is encoded and transmitted using Frequency Shift Keying (FSK), a digital modulation technique known for reliable data transmission.

5. Receiver & Interface

The receiver decodes the transmitted signal and displays the detected gesture as text or speech using a visualization interface.

